m":"Wolverley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1450–ABT 1529":"circa 1450–circa 1529","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1480–Male":"1480–Overleden","1490–Female":"1490–Overleden","1492–1574":"1492–1574","1500–1522":"1500–1522","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1450–1529":"1450–1529","about 1480":"circa 1480","ABT 1529":"circa 1529","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1574":"1574","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","about 1450":"circa 1450","Wolverley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverley, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1450–ABT 1529":"about 1450–about 1529","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1480–Male":"1480–Deceased","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","1492–1574":"1492–1574","1500–1522":"1500–1522","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1450–1529":"1450–1529","about 1480":"about 1480","ABT 1529":"about 1529","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1574":"1574","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","about 1450":"about 1450","Wolverley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lewis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Lewis</i>, <i>Leweis</i>, <i>Lowis</i>, from ancient Germanic (originally West Frankish) <i>Hludwig</i> (itself from <i>hlōd-</i> ‘fame, famous’ + <i>wīg-</i> ‘battle’). This was Latinized as <i>Ludovicus</i> and <i>Chlodovisus</i>, which were gallicized as <i>Clovis</i> or <i>Clouis</i>, French <i>Louis</i>. The name may also appear as <i>Lawis</i>, <i>Laweys</i>, <i>Lawes</i>, by unrounding of the vowel of <i>Lowis</i> on the analogy of the variation between <i>Low</i> and <i>Law</i> as pet forms of Middle English <i>Lourence</i> alias <i>Laurence</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Laws   2 and compare   Lawrence  .","Welsh: adopted for the Welsh personal name <i>Llywelyn</i> (see   Llewellyn  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’. This is one of the most common Old Irish personal names. It is derived from <i>Lugh</i> ‘brightness’, which was the name of a Celtic god."],"variants":[{"name":"Laws","meanings":["English: variant of   Law   (pet form of   Lawrence  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish or Irish   McLeish  . Compare   McLaws  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"McGlew","meanings":["Irish: most probably from <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’, a Gaelic personal name (referencing the god Lugh), sometimes Anglicized as   Lewis  . However, both Woulfe and MacLysaght consider <i>McGlew</i> to be a shortened form of <b>Mac Dhuinnshléibhe</b> (see   McAleavey   and   Dunleavy  )."]},{"name":"Lowis","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewis   1."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Cecilia Mary Lewis was born about 1450, in London, Middlesex, England. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Henry Hayte Winwood. She died about 1529, in her hometown, at the age of 81."},"et":{"about 1450–ABT 1529":"umbes 1450–umbes 1529","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","1492–1574":"1492–1574","1500–1522":"1500–1522","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1450–1529":"1450–1529","about 1480":"umbes 1480","ABT 1529":"umbes 1529","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1574":"1574","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Wolverley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverley, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1450–ABT 1529":"noin 145